occurrences.line_text: Thereof full blyth the Lady streight became,
And me in lieu thereof reuil'd againe,
There he the necke thereof did cut in twaine,
Witnesse thereof he shew'd his head there left,
Him selfe thereof he labour'd to acquite,
That he could not thereof auenged bee:
To weet what issue would thereof betyde,
Him heedlesse bit, the whiles he was thereof secure.
At sight thereof, and from her presence flee:
And how thereof her selfe she did acquite,
Thereof false Turpin was full glad and faine,
But she thereof grew proud and insolent,
That seemed nought the course thereof could stay:
Ne list the Knight the powre thereof assay,
Thereof by force to take their beastly pleasure.
And at the foote thereof, a gentle flud
And on the top thereof a spacious plaine
Should know thereof, to slay he would haue sought,
The litle babe, to take thereof a sight.
But Calidore thereof no whit afrayd,
Of that deare Lord, who oft thereon was fownd,
As he thereon stood gazing, he might see
For happie life to all, which thereon fed,
And holy water thereon sprinckled wide;
Thereon an yron lock did fasten firme and strong.
And thereon sat a woman gorgeous gay,
His foot thereon, may neuer it recure,
The verdant grasse, as he thereon did tread;
They did him set thereon, and forthwith them conuayd.
When the bright sunne his beams thereon doth beat;
Ne the sharp Northerne wind thereon to showre,
He much more goodly glosse thereon doth shed,
From heaping stroakes, which thereon soused sore:
And thundred strokes thereon so hideouslie,
That he thereon should spin both flax and tow;
But tooke her steede, and thereon mounting light,
But thought, that she thereon could neuer gaze her fill.
But first the Tygre clawes thereon did lay;
Vp to the rocke he ran, and thereon flew
Thereon distill, and deaw her daintie face,
Which thereon seizing, tooke no great effect;
Earst chawd thereon, yet was not all so dead,
The eyes of all, which thereon fixed beene;
By his owne sword, and by the crosse thereon,
To saluage chace, where I thereon may hit
Into his wounds, him vp thereon did reare,
And being thereon mounted, forth did pace,
For loue in soft delight thereon to rest;
To offer sacrifice diuine thereon;
The litle purple rose, which thereon grew,
And heauenly documents thereout did preach,
That drops of purple bloud thereout did weepe,
Did cast about by sleight the truth thereout to straine.
Whose grudging ghost was thereout fled and past,
For wheres no courage, theres no ruth nor mone.
He thereto meeting said, My dearest Dame,
Thereto said he, Faire Dame be nought dismaid
And thereto added words of wondrous might:
Whom rauenous hunger did thereto constraine:
For nigh thereto the euer damned beast
Thereto his subtile engins he does bend
Full loth she seemd thereto, but yet did faine;
Which done, he balmes and herbes thereto applyde,
Thereto as cold and drery as a Snake,
Him faild thereto, and serued not his need,
That mote the passengers thereto allure;
Thereto the Heauens alwayes Iouiall,
But when thereto they might not be allured,
Thereto so bounteous and so debonaire,
And all the while sweet birdes thereto applide
Great aid thereto his mighty puissaunce,
Thereto he was a doughtie dreaded knight,
Thereto so swift, that it all beasts did pas:
Thereto feare gaue her wings, and neede her courage taught.
But she thereto would lend but light regard,
Who thereto answering, said; the tydings bad,
Thereto her feare was made so much the greater
By sundry meanes thereto she prickt him forth,
Thereto she was right faire, when so her face
Thereto she learned was in Magicke leare,
And thereto all his power and might applide:
For saluage wight, and thereto well agreed
The iudges which thereto selected were,
But by no meanes they could it thereto frame.
But Britomart would not thereto assent,
Thereto him Ate stird, new discord to maintaine.
And rend a sunder quite, if he thereto list striue.
Still as aduantage they espyde thereto:
No longer space thereto he did desire,
Till I thereto had all things ready dight.
Thereto the villaine vsed craft in fight;
And drew thereto, making her eare her guide.
And eke his garment, to be thereto meet,
His noble hart; thereto she did annexe
Who thereto did with readie will consent,
Thereto he offred for to make him chiefe
Albe that Hatred was thereto full loth,
Thereto he was expert in prophecies,
Do you by duresse him compell thereto,
Thereto they both did franckly condiscend,
But he thereto would by no meanes consent;
Thereto he hath a groome of euill guize,
Thereto she is full faire, and rich attired,
But he for nought could him thereto constraine.
Them selues thereto preparde in order dew;
And thereto did himselfe right well behaue,
Yet would she not thereto yeeld free accord,
Thereto compelled through hart-murdring paine,
And als' of princely grace to be inclyn'd thereto.
Say, and do all, that may thereto preuaile;
Thereto adde art, euen womens witty trade,
But by no meanes could her thereto perswade:
Thereto both his owne wylie wit, (she sayd)
Till strong constraint did her thereto enforce.
Thereto a great aduauntage eke he has
Thereto addresse, and his bright shield display.
Thereto the body of a dog she had,
Thereto he had great skill in single fight:
Hung loose and loathsomely: Thereto her hew
Thereto the Blatant beast by them set on
Nathlesse thereto he was full stout and tall,
Thereto great helpe dame Nature selfe doth lend:
Sir Calidore his faith thereto did plight,
What euer formes ye list thereto apply,
And nigh thereto a little Chappell stoode,
So long as age enabled him thereto,
Thereto, when needed, she could weepe and pray,
For that himselfe thereto did want sufficient might.
But she thereto nould plead, nor answere ought
Thereto they vsde one most accursed order,
One word durst speake, or answere him a whit thereto.
The knight full gladly soone agreed thereto,
Thereto approch, ne filth mote therein drowne:
Thereto they all attonce agreed well,
Thereto they soone agreed, and earnest tooke,
That might her loue prepare, and liking win theretoo.
Feared in vaine, sith meanes ye see there wants theretoo.
Taken in hand th'exploit, being theretoo
Next thereunto did grow a goodly tree,
Therefore old Syre thy course do thereunto apply.
But when she mote not thereunto be wonne,
Eftsoones her steps she thereunto applyde,
Not by strong hand compelled thereunto,
And all his powre doth thereunto apply:
Ne ought to answere thereunto did find;
And all his powre applyed thereunto,
Vnlesse that I were thereunto enforst.
And thereunto a great long chaine he tight,
And he himselfe long gazing thereupon,
She warn'd the knights thereof: who thereupon
Like a triumphall Arch, and thereupon
So stood he still long gazing thereupon,
And his accuser thereuppon defide:
Downe to her lowest heele, and thereuppon
And thereuppon long while stood gazing still,
So thereuppon long while she musing lay,
Therewith enrag'd she loudly gan to bray,
Therewith she spewd out of her filthy maw
And hide thy head. Therewith vpon his crest
Therewith a piteous yelling voyce was heard,
Therewith she gan her passion to renew,
Therewith in haste his helmet gan vnlace,
Therewith they gan to hurtlen greedily,
Therewith redoubled was his raging yre,
Therewith vpon his crest he stroke him so,
Therewith his heauie hand he high gan reare,
Therewith the knight thence marched forth in hast,
Therewith they gan, both furious and fell,
And trees did tremble. Th'Elfe therewith astownd,
Men into stones therewith he could transmew,
Therewith the Gyant buckled him to fight,
Therewith his sturdie courage soone was quayd,
Therewith an hollow, dreary, murmuring voyce
And therewith all enwrapt the nimble thyes
And therewith scourge the buxome aire so sore,
Therewith at last he forst him to vnty
Therewith amoued from his sober mood,
Therewith her dim eie-lids she vp gan reare,
Therewith all suddeinly he seemd enraged,
Therewith Sir Guyon left his first emprise,
Therewith she laught, and did her earnest end in iest.
Therewith she sweetly smyld. They though full bent,
Therewith to doen his foes eternall smart.
His Lords owne flesh. Therewith out of his hond
Against the Pagans brest, and therewith thought
And therewith all attonce at him let fly
And therewith loudly laught: But nathemore
Of hungry eies, which n'ote therewith be fild,
Therewith a while she her flit fancy fed,
And the whole family therewith adred,
Surprisd her sense: she therewith well apayd,
Therewith th'Enchaunter softly gan to smyle
And therewith crowne himselfe in th'others stead:
And therewith shot an arrow at the lad;
The flesh therewith she suppled and did steepe,
Therewith he sigh'd, and turning him aside,
But Phoebe therewith sore was angered,
Yet therewith sore enrag'd, with sterne regard
To get small thankes, and therewith many blames,
He was therewith distressed diuersly,
Great store of treasure, therewith him to tempt;
The same behold, therewith their keene desires were whet.
Who therewith somewhat starting, vp gan looke,
Therewith resolu'd to proue her vtmost might,
He stearnly shooke, and therewith fierce did stryke
Nought therewith daunted was her courage proud,
Exceeding wroth therewith the virgin grew,
Therewith she stayd her hand, loth stayd to bee;
Therewith their dulled sprights they edgd anew,
Therewith a sunder in the midst it brast,
And therewith smote him on his Vmbriere
Beheld, he woxe therewith displeased sore,
Therewith to bind lasciuious desire,
Therewith, as thing deuiz'd her to defame.
Out of the burning cinders, and therewith
And therewith stroke at her so hideouslie,
He was therewith right wondrously dismayd,
Therewith her wrathfull courage gan appall,
Therewith he rested, and well pleased was.
But her therewith full sore displeasd he found,
Yet he therewith so felly still did raue,
His greedy throte, therewith in two distraught,
Therewith she rose in hast, and her addrest
Therewith both Squire and dwarfe did tomble downe
And therewith smote at him with all his might.
Who mou'd no more therewith, then when a rocke
Who all that comes doth take, and therewith fill
Therewith the Gyant much abashed sayd;
He was therewith exceedingly dismayd;
Therewith much comforted, she gan vnfold
Therewith she gan at first to change her mood,
Therewith containes his heauenly Common-weale,
For that therewith he falsely did reuyle,
Therewith, all fraught with fury and disdaine,
And Belge selfe was therewith stonied sore,
Most vgly filth, and poyson therewith rusht,
Therewith Grandtorto selfe I did appall,
That he therewith the knight drew all about:
And whiles he combred was therewith so sore,
And as she spake, therewith she slauered;
Who nathelesse not therewith satisfyde,
He therewith much abashed and affrayd,
Therewith the cowheard deaded with affright,
Her therewith yirks, and still when she complaines,
Who therewith flesht, vpon him set anew,
And from him taking his owne whip, therewith
Therewith some other of the chiefest theeues
Therewith he mured vp his mouth along,
And therewithall he fiercely at him flew,
And manly terrour mixed therewithall,
Vpon her snowy cheeke; and therewithall
That he was soone awaked therewithall,
And therewithall at him right furiously she strooke.
To whom I cald aloud, halfe angry therewithall.
Departed straight to Proteus therewithall:
But he was nothing mou'd, nor tempted therewithall.
The same longwhile I bore, and therewithall
And made such piteous mourning therewithall,
Thought therewithall forthwith him to haue slaine,
And therewithall rude hand on him did lay.
The warrant straight was made, and therewithall
His manly mynde was much emmoued therewithall.
She sudden was reuiued therewithall,
Did cast his shield atweene, and therewithall
Were housed therewithin, whom he enlargen might.
And therfore wisht me stay, till I more truth should fynd.
Therfore do you my rimes keep better measure,
To Therion, a loose vnruly swayne;
But that in stead therof, she sternely bade
His feeble steps, which shrunke, when hard theron he lay.
So stood these twaine, vnmoued as a rocke,
Sends to my doubtfull eares these speaches rare,
Nor guilefull sprite, to thee these wordes doth speake,
That my fraile eyes these lines with teares do steepe,
All these, and many euils moe haunt ire,
All these together in one heape were throwne,
Amongst these mighty men were wemen mixt,
And lastly throwne themselues into these heauy stowres.
And then to him these womanish words gan say;
In these and like delights of bloudy game
These eyes did see that knight both liuing and eke ded.
So fiersly, when these knights had breathed once,
Wherewith he all enrag'd, these bitter speaches said.
The which these reliques sad present vnto mine eie.
Wherewith emmou'd, these bleeding words she gan to say.
Whom these sad eyes saw nigh vnto deaths dore,
These piteous plaints and dolours did resound;
And for these wrongs shall treble penaunce pay
And maister these mishaps with patient might;
Till he these wordes to him deliuer might;
And foltring tongue at last these words seemd forth to shake.
Who when these two approching he aspide,
These that haue it attaind, were in like cace
That all these sorrowes suffer for my sake,
Her greeting sends in these sad lines addrest,
When he these bitter byting words had red,
What meane these bloudy vowes, and idle threats,
Yet all these were, when no man did them know;
These words she breathed forth from riuen chest;
In these sad words she spent her vtmost breath:
Which to these Ladies loue did countenaunce,
These two gay knights, vowd to so diuerse loues,
Is this the ioy of armes? be these the parts
From lofty siege began these words aloud to sound.
Of all my sorrow, and of these sad teares,
Not this rude kind of battell, nor these armes
These flames, these flames (he cryde) do me torment.
These flames, these flames (he cryde) do me torment.
And these rich heapes of wealth doest hide apart
At thy commaund lo all these mountaines bee;
All these may not suffise, there shall to thee
Ne wote I, but thou didst these goods bereaue
Ne toung did tell, ne hand these handled not,
All these before the gates of Pluto lay,
To them, that list, these base regardes I lend:
In heauenly spirits to these creatures bace,
But leaue these relicks of his liuing might,
But at these straungers presence euery one did hush.
Might be compar'd to these by many parts:
With these in praise of pollicies mote striue.
These three in these three roomes did sundry dwell,
These three in these three roomes did sundry dwell,
But that the same could one of these comprize.
In meed of these great conquests by them got,
From whence he brought them to these saluage parts,
Then all the sonnes of these fiue brethren raynd
Of these a mightie people shortly grew,
After all these Elficleos did rayne,
Thus these twelue troupes with dreadfull puissance
By these rent reliques, speaking their ill plights?
All these, and thousand thousands many more,
Ne wonder, if these did the knight appall;
For these same Monsters are not these in deed,
For these same Monsters are not these in deed,
But are into these fearefull shapes disguiz'd
Said he, These seeming beasts are men indeed,
These sixe would me enforce by oddes of might,
These straunger knights through passing, forth were led
For such intent into these parts I came,
And said, Sir knight, these idle termes forbeare,
For not of nought these suddeine ghastly feares
These idle words (said she) doe nought asswage
Vnto these Sprights, to bring to perfect end.
Yet after all these sorrowes, and huge hills
Yet shall a third both these, and thine subdew;
Late dayes ensample, which these eyes beheld,
Yet these, and all that else had puissaunce,
Which in these troubled bowels raignes, & rageth rife.
That so deepe wound through these deare members driue.
All these I wote in thy protection bee,
These two were twinnes, & twixt them two did share
Conceiu'd these infants, and how them she bare,
So sprong these twinnes in wombe of Chrysogone,
But when in none of all these she him got,
These twinnes, men say, (a thing far passing thought)
These eyes did see, that they will euer rew
But all the while, that he these speaches spent,
So long these knights discoursed diuersly,
Suffred, these seuen monethes day in secret den
And leaning on his elbow, these few wordes let fly.
What is there else, but cease these fruitlesse paines,
Whiles thus on earth great Ioue these pageaunts playd,
Thus marched these sixe couples forth in faire degree.
After all these there marcht a most faire Dame,
The which these Stoicke censours cannot well deny.
That to Sir Paridell these words he sent;
How may these rimes, so rude as doth appeare,
These three did loue each other dearely well,
These three so noble babes to bring forth at one clap.
Got these three louely babes, that prov'd three cha[m]pions bold.
These three that hardie chalenge tooke in hand,
These warlike Champions all in armour shine,
So cruelly these Knights stroue for that Ladies sake.
So these two champions to the ground were feld,
So did these two through all the field their foes enforce.
And after these an hundred Ladies moe
And eke with these, full many other Knights
During which space these sory eies haue seen
In these wild woods, as was her wonted ioy,
Here well I weene, when as these rimes be red
These gentle Ladies will misdeeme too light,
In which these Squires true friendship more did sway,
These paires of friends in peace and setled rest,
So diuersly these foure disposed were to loue.
All these together by themselves did sport
But farre away from these, another sort
Which loued not as these, for like intent,
All these and all that euer had bene tyde,
These marched farre afore the other crew;
Next these the plenteous Ouse came far from land,
Next these came Tyne, along whose stony bancke
These after, came the stony shallow Lone,
All these together marched toward Proteus hall.
These three faire sons, which being the[n]ce forth powrd
And after these the Sea Nymphs marched all,
All these the daughters of old Nereus were,
But well I wote, that these which I descry,
Such oddes I finde twixt those, and these which are,
Their setting forth, in these few thousand yeares
That doth enlumine all these lesser fyres,
Such was betwixt these two the troublesome vprore.
In which they doe these many yeares remaine,
Therefore I will throw downe these mountaines hie,
These towring rocks, which reach vnto the skie,
But if the weight of these thou canst not show,
And all these knights, which that day armour bore,
And these the signes, (so shewed forth his wounds)
Now when these counterfeits were thus vncased
Seem'd that for it these Squires at ods did fall,
But these conditions doe to him propound,
These noble warriors, mindefull to pursew
With these his wicked sons, and shewd his cankred hate.
These vile reproches gan vnto her speake;
Soone after these he saw another Knight,
These two false Knights, whom there ye lying see,
Such was the furie of these head-strong steeds,
Through these his slights he many doth confound,
When these two stranger knights arriu'd in place,
But at the sight of these, those were a while debard.
Therefore these two, her eldest sonnes she sent,
Onely these marishes, and myrie bogs,
Vppon these warriours, greedy t'vnderstand,
And these weake impes replanted by thy might;
Against these pesants, which haue me opprest,
These two now had themselues combynd in one,
Such were these Hags, and so vnhandsome drest:
In these strange waies, where neuer foote did vse,
To heare these tidings, which of none afore
With these conditions, which I will propound:
So long as these two armes were able to be wroken.
He burst into these words, as to him seemed good.
That in these woods amongst the Nymphs dost wonne,
(Vnlesse thou in these woods thy selfe conceale,
Such be our ioyes, which in these forrests grow:
And being now high time these strong ioynts to imploy.
These goodly gilden armes, which I haue won in fight.
These eyes him saw vpon the cold earth sprad,
That he these words burst forth; Ah sory boy,
Thether he brought these vnacquainted guests;
But to these happie fortunes, cruell Fate
All these our ioyes, and all our blisse abate;
To these sicke twaine, that now began to droupe,
Whenas these Knights arriu'd, they wist not where nor how.
Of these poore folk, whose soules with black dishonor
Yet had she not in all these two yeares space,
These two, vnworthy of your wretched bands;
So did these two this Knight oft tug and teare.
With these two lewd companions, and no more,
That for these Carles to carry much more comely were?
Whether I shall you leaue, or from these villaines lose.
In these wylde deserts, where she now abode,
Till being waked with these loud alarmes,
From all the tempests of these worldly seas,
Frequented of these gentle Nymphes alwayes,
Tell me, what mote these dainty Damzels be,
These three on men all gracious gifts bestow,
The dwelling of these shepheards did inuade,
Whylest thus she in these hellish dens remayned,
By some of these same theeues at the instant brunt,
These marchants fixed eyes did so amaze,
These eyes saw die, and dearely did lament:
When Calidore these ruefull newes had raught,
For on her brest I with these eyes did vew
Theseus condemned to endlesse slouth by law,
Stout Theseus, and Pirithous his feare;
Like as the cursed sonne of Theseus,
That Theseus her vnto his bridale bore,
Or the Thessalian Tempe, where of yore
Them thether brought, and how their harmes befell.
I thether went where I did long conceale
And thether also came in open sight
He thether came, but for to trie the right
Thether he brought these vnacquainted guests;
Him thether eke for all his fearefull threat
If such a beast they saw, which he had thether brought.
Till time that Calidore brought Pastorella thether.
All arm'd to point came ryding thetherward,
The chaulky Kenet, and the Thetis gray,
Swift Proto, milde Eucrate, Thetis faire,
Of Thetis wedding with ï¿½acidee,
Yet would not seeme so rude, and thewed ill,
To be vpbrought in gentle thewes and martiall might.
In goodly thewes, and godly exercise:
For well ye worthie bene for worth and gentle thewes.
Who in all godly thewes, and goodly prayse
He with good thewes and speaches well applyde,
Yet praise likewise deserue good thewes, enforst with paine.
In gentle thewes, and such like seemely leres.
And it in goodly thewes so well vpbrought,
Of needments at his backe. Thus as they past,
A shadie groue not far away they spide,
Faire harbour that them seemes; so in they entred arre.
And foorth they passe, with pleasure forward led,
Much can they prayse the trees so straight and hy,
Led with delight, they thus beguile the way,
When weening to returne, whence they did stray,
They cannot finde that path, which first was showne,
Furthest from end then, when they neerest weene,
That which of them to take, in diuerse doubt they been.
Till that some end they finde or in or out,
